TableContextTimeStampBeforeTable: {3796=Ross, along with friends Mary Wilson, Florence Ballard, and Barbara Martin, formed the Primettes vocal group back in 1959. The quartet changed its name upon signing with Motown Records, and after Martin left the group, the remaining three continued as a trio. Eventually the group became known as "Diana Ross and the Supremes" and ultimately went on to land a dozen number one hits. Following the last one, "Someday We'll Be Together" in 1969, Ross went on to launch her solo career., 1917=The legendary Diana Ross will be bringing her iconic music throughout North America this summer. The former Supreme will kick things off in the home of Motown, Detroit (Sterling Heights, to be specific) on June 13. From there, Ross will head through Cincinnati, playing on June 14, and on to a run through the Northeast…, 2710=The incomparable Diana Ross was honored by the cable television network BET with a Lifetime Achievement Award back in 2007. She was the recipient of a similar honor from the Recording Academy with the Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award in 2012. Ross has sold more than 100 million records worldwide, and still, her career is far from over. She continues to tour and is currently trekking through the U.S. in 2014. Internet rumors have also surfaced of a new album coming soon produced by Mary J. Blige.}
